Module jtrim.collections
Package org.jtrim2.collections

Class ElementRefIterator<E>

java.lang.Object
org.jtrim2.collections.ElementRefIterator<E>
Type Parameters:
E - the type of the elements iterated by this Iterator
All Implemented Interfaces:
Iterator<RefList.ElementRef<E>>, ListIterator<RefList.ElementRef<E>>
public final class ElementRefIterator<E> extends Object implements ListIterator<RefList.ElementRef<E>>
A convenient ListIterator for iterating through the element references of a RefList. This Iterator will use RefList.ElementRef.getNext(int) and RefList.ElementRef.getPrevious(int) method of the element references and the iterator remains valid even if the underlying list is changed while it is being iterated (Removing from the underlying list however risks making the iterator an empty iterator). Note however that it doesn't imply thread-safety.

This implementation supports removing elements if the underlying list implementation supports it. Note that the set and the add methods are not supported and will throw unchecked exceptions. Instead it provides the setElement(E) and the addElement(E) methods as a replacement.

Warning: There are three limitations of this implementation:

  • If the element last returned by the iterator (either by next() or previous()), this iterator immediately becomes an empty iterator. In case no element was returned yet, the current element is the starting element specified at construction time. Removing an element returned by next() makes the previous element the current element (except when at the beginning of the underlying list where chooses the next element) and removing an element returned by previous() makes the next element the current element (except when at the end of the underlying list where chooses the previous element).
  • Once the iterator becomes an empty iterator (by any means), adding new elements will no longer modify the underlying list.
  • If the iterator is empty and new element is added through this iterator, it will use a newly created RefLinkedList as an underlying list and not the one used to back this list before it contained element.

Thread safety

Instances of this class are not safe to use by multiple concurrent threads if at least one of them modifies the underlying list even if the underlying list implementation is thread-safe.

Synchronization transparency

This class derives its synchronization transparency from the underlying RefList object. Note however that in general java.util.Collection Collection implementations are expected to be completely synchronization transparent.

    • setElement

      public void setElement(E element)
      Replaces the last element of the reference returned by next() or previous() with the specified element. This call can be made only if neither remove() nor add(org.jtrim2.collections.RefList.ElementRef<E>) have been called after the last call to next or previous.
      Parameters:
      element - the element with which to replace the last element returned by next or previous
      Throws:
      ClassCastException - if the class of the specified element prevents it from being added to this list
      IllegalArgumentException - if some aspect of the specified element prevents it from being added to the underlying list
      IllegalStateException - if neither next nor previous have been called, or remove or add have been called after the last call to next or previous

    • addElement

      public void addElement(E element)
      Inserts the specified element into the list. The element is inserted immediately before the element that would be returned by next(), if any, and after the element that would be returned by previous(), if any. (If the list contains no elements, the new element becomes the sole element on the list.) The new element is inserted before the implicit cursor: a subsequent call to next would be unaffected, and a subsequent call to previous would return the new element. (This call increases by one the value that would be returned by a call to nextIndex or previousIndex.)
      Parameters:
      element - the element to insert
      Throws:
      ClassCastException - if the class of the specified element prevents it from being added to this list
      IllegalArgumentException - if some aspect of this element prevents it from being added to this list
